inner_edges_g.loc[~edges["highway"].isin(['cycleway', 'footway', 'pedestrian', 'trail', 'crossing'])].shape
  1. inner_edges_g: This variable represents an OSM GeoPandas dataframe. It likely contains information related to street networks or road segments. 'highway', 'length', and more. 3..loc[~edges["highway"].isin(['cycleway', 'footway', 'pedestrian', 'trail', 'crossing'])]: This part of the code filters the rows in the edges GeoDataFrame. It selects only those rows where the value in the highway column does not match any of the specified road types: 'cycleway', 'footway', 'pedestrian', 'trail', or 'crossing'. 4..shape: Finally, .shape returns a tuple representing the dimensions of the resulting filtered GeoDataFrame. The first value in the tuple is the number of rows (representing the filtered street segments), and the second value is the number of columns.

In summary, this code snippet calculates the shape (number of rows and columns) of the filtered GeoDataFrame containing street segments that are not cycleways, footways, pedestrian paths, trails, or crossings. It’s a way to extract relevant road segments for further analysis or visualization. 🛣️🗺️

In [ ]:
# OSM data is in WGS84 so typically we need to use lat/lon coordinates when searching for the closest node

# Origin
orig_address = "Koszykowa 86, Warsaw"
orig_y, orig_x = ox.geocode(orig_address)  # notice the coordinate order (y, x)!

# Destination
dest_address = "Nowogrodzka 49, Warsaw"
dest_y, dest_x = ox.geocode(dest_address)

print("Origin coords:", orig_x, orig_y)
print("Destination coords:", dest_x, dest_y)

Origin coords: 20.994374497812714 52.223936
Destination coords: 21.0072621 52.2274915
In [ ]:
# 1. Find the closest nodes for origin and destination
orig_node_id, dist_to_orig = ox.distance.nearest_nodes(G, X=orig_x, Y=orig_y, return_dist=True)
dest_node_id, dist_to_dest = ox.distance.nearest_nodes(G, X=dest_x, Y=dest_y, return_dist=True)

print("Origin node-id:", orig_node_id, "and distance:", dist_to_orig, "meters.")
print("Destination node-id:", dest_node_id, "and distance:", dist_to_dest, "meters.")

Origin node-id: 10937948740 and distance: 4.165578312416032 meters.
Destination node-id: 9503355049 and distance: 15.126932381293551 meters.
In [ ]:
# Calculate the paths by walking and cycling
metric_path = nx.dijkstra_path(G, source=orig_node_id, target=dest_node_id, weight='length')
time_path = nx.dijkstra_path(G, source=orig_node_id, target=dest_node_id, weight='travel_time_seconds')

# Get also the actual travel times (summarize)
travel_length = nx.dijkstra_path_length(G, source=orig_node_id, target=dest_node_id, weight='length')
travel_time = nx.dijkstra_path_length(G, source=orig_node_id, target=dest_node_id, weight='travel_time_seconds')
